"1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Anglie","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Beverly, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Anglie","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1 January 1400–1 January 1490":"1. januar 1400–1. januar 1490","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1484":"1428–1484","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1432–1472":"1432–1472","1434–1500":"1434–1500","1325–1410":"1325–1410","1330–Female":"1330–Afdød","1 January 1490":"1. januar 1490","1484":"1484","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1490":"1490","1 January 1400":"1. januar 1400","1325":"1325","1434":"1434","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Beverly, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Jórvík, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1 January 1400–1 January 1490":"1 januari 1400–1 januari 1490","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1484":"1428–1484","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1432–1472":"1432–1472","1434–1500":"1434–1500","1325–1410":"1325–1410","1330–Female":"1330–Overleden","1 January 1490":"1 januari 1490","1484":"1484","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1490":"1490","1 January 1400":"1 januari 1400","1325":"1325","1434":"1434","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Beverly, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1 January 1400–1 January 1490":"1 January 1400–1 January 1490","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1484":"1428–1484","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1432–1472":"1432–1472","1434–1500":"1434–1500","1325–1410":"1325–1410","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1 January 1490":"1 January 1490","1484":"1484","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1490":"1490","1 January 1400":"1 January 1400","1325":"1325","1434":"1434","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Beverly, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alcok</i>, a pet form of any of the many medieval personal names beginning with <i>Al-</i>, especially <i>Alan</i> and <i>Alexander</i>. The Middle English hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i> (see   Cocke  ) was very commonly added to personal names in Middle English: compare for example   Hancock   and   Wilcock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Allicock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Allcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Alcott","meanings":["English: ostensibly a topographic name from any of a large number of places called in Old English as ‘the old cottage’ (Old English <i>(e)ald</i> + <i>cot(e)</i>). In fact, however, it is generally an altered form of   Alcock  , in part at least for euphemistic reasons.","History: Louisa May Alcott (1832–88), author of <i>Little Women</i> (1869), was the daughter of Amos Bronson Alcott (1799–1888), who had changed the surname from <i>Alcox</i>. The family trace their descent from an Alcocke family who emigrated from England to MA with John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ) in 1630."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Alcock was born on 1 January 1400, in Beverley, Yorkshire, England, his father, John Alcock, was 75 and his mother, Mrs. John Alcock, was 71. He married Catherine in 1429, in Beverley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 1 January 1490, in his hometown, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1 January 1400–1 January 1490":"1. jaanuar 1400–1. jaanuar 1490","1400–1490":"1400–1490","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1484":"1428–1484","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1432–1472":"1432–1472","1434–1500":"1434–1500","1325–1410":"1325–1410","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1 January 1490":"1. jaanuar 1490","1484":"1484","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1490":"1490","1 January 1400":"1. jaanuar 1400","1325":"1325","1434":"1434","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1432":"1432","1430":"1430","1429":"1429","1428":"1428","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beverly, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, England","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"